<subSubSection id="2CDE41C4F55F3F3E4B90EC0BF8C3C7A0" pageId="83" pageNumber="94" type="description">
<paragraph id="647B124FF55F3F3E4B90EC0BF8C2C4D6" blockId="83.[433,1833,370,1736]" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">
Runs to 
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF55F3F3E48E8EC0BFCCFC2E4" box="[648,811,867,908]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">thermalis</emphasis>
in Horvath's key (Hist.-Nat. Mus. Nat. Hung.,.Ann. 
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF55F3F3E4C8EEC0BF8F6C2E4" bold="true" box="[1774,1810,867,908]" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">13:</emphasis>
544, 1915) but lacks the two subbasal black tubercles of the first genital segment of that European species. 
<taxonomicName id="A3C469CCF55F3F3E4E6EECA1FA43C29B" authority="Kirkaldy" authorityName="Kirkaldy" authorityYear="1901" box="[1038,1447,969,1011]" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="83" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF55F3F3E4E6EECA1FB12C29B" box="[1038,1270,969,1011]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">M. orientalis</emphasis>
Kirkaldy
</taxonomicName>
is superficially quite similar but has a distinct median tubercle on the first genital segment. The present species differs from 
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF55F3F3E49DAEB59FBC0C531" box="[954,1060,1073,1113]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">indica</emphasis>
Horvath, in which the second segment of the hind tarsus is shorter than the third and the eyes are not sinuate at inner baJ,es, and in which no mention is made of the black bristles found in 
<taxonomicName id="A3C469CCF55F3F3E4CC5EBFFF8CCC5D7" box="[1701,1832,1175,1215]" class="Insecta" family="Rhyparochromidae" genus="Pamera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="83" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacifica">
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF55F3F3E4CC5EBFFF8CCC5D7" box="[1701,1832,1175,1215]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">pacifica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the first genital segment. 
<taxonomicName id="A3C469CCF55F3F3E49D2EBA2FACCC59B" authority="Hale" authorityName="Hale" authorityYear="1926" box="[946,1320,1226,1267]" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="83" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hungerfordi">
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF55F3F3E49D2EBA2FB23C59B" box="[946,1223,1226,1267]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">M. hungerfordi</emphasis>
Hale
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="1CD352DFF55F3F3E4FFAEBA2F9DAC59B" box="[1434,1598,1226,1267]" name="Australia" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">Australia</collectingCountry>
is larger and has &quot;two elevated tufts of brownish-black spines on the venter of the first genital segment&quot; (Hale, South Austr. Mus., Rec. 3: 200, 1926) as in 
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF55F3F3E4CB7EA58FC30C4E4" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">mulsanti,thermalis,andsubvittata.</emphasis>
Thespinesthatcompriseth!ise &quot;tufts&quot; arevery short and dense in contrast to the long, posteriorly directed bristles of 
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF55F3F3E4CFBEAFEF8C2C4D6" box="[1691,1830,1430,1470]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">
<taxonomicName id="A3C469CCF55F3F3E4CFBEAFEF8C5C4D6" box="[1691,1825,1430,1470]" class="Insecta" family="Rhyparochromidae" genus="Pamera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="83" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacifica">pacifica</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="647B124FF55F3F3E4B92EAB8F8C3C7A0" blockId="83.[433,1833,370,1736]" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">
The only other 
<taxonomicName id="A3C469CCF55F3F3E496AEAB8FC59C493" authorityName="Mulsant &amp; Rey" authorityYear="1852" box="[778,957,1488,1531]" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="83" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF55F3F3E496AEAB8FC59C493" box="[778,957,1488,1531]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">Mesovelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
reported from an oceanic island in the Pacific is 
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF55F3F3E4BD3E96CFDADC746" box="[435,585,1540,1582]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">mulsanti</emphasis>
White (fig. 25, 
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF55F3F3E4916E96CFC43C746" box="[886,935,1540,1582]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">c),</emphasis>
a common species in taro patches in the lowlands of the Hawaiian Islands. This was doubtless introduced quite recently from America. I have seen a Fijian 
<taxonomicName id="A3C469CCF55F3F3E4E6AE903FB59C7FC" authorityName="Mulsant &amp; Rey" authorityYear="1852" box="[1034,1213,1643,1684]" class="Insecta" family="Mesoveliidae" genus="Mesovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="83" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56B0CE5DF55F3F3E4E6AE903FB59C7FC" box="[1034,1213,1643,1684]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">Mesovelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the recent collection of E. C. Zimmerman and 
<collectingCountry id="1CD352DFF55F3F3E4881E9F6FC0EC7A0" box="[737,1002,1694,1736]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="83" pageNumber="94">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
specimens in the collections of F. X. Williams.
</paragraph>
